      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Alveolar Fricatives in Coda",
          "textSize": "heading-one"
        }
      ],
      "align": "center"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-three",
          "text": "Articulation/Orthographic Representation "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "In phonetics (the study of how linguistic sound is physically produced), sounds are named by first the place of articulation in the mouth, and second by the manner of articulation. So, an "
        },
        {
          "text": "alveolar",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " (place) "
        },
        {
          "text": "fricative",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " (manner) is a sound where the tongue touches the alveolar ridge right behind our upper incisors while producing frication, which happens when a lot of very fast-moving air escapes from around the tongue. In English and Spanish, this sound is represented in writing mostly with an < s > and sometimes a < c > (e.g., la"
        },
        {
          "text": "s",
          "underline": true
        },
        {
          "text": " "
        },
        {
          "text": "c",
          "underline": true
        },
        {
          "text": "inco "
        },
        {
          "text": "s",
          "underline": true
        },
        {
          "text": "illa"
        },
        {
          "text": "s",
          "underline": true
        },
        {
          "text": "). In the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA), this sound is represented with an "
        },
        {
          "text": "/s/",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "text": ". "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "horizontal-separator",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "/s/ Reduction ",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "One of the most widely discussed features of Caribbean Spanish and a central resource in reggaetón is the variable realization of syllable-final /s/ (e.g., "
        },
        {
          "text": "los mismos",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": ").  Historically, this feature traces back to Southern Spain in Seville and Andalusia, where processes of consonant weakening began as early as the 16th century in lower-class speech before spreading upward through the social hierarchy and outward through colonial expansion. As a result, varieties of Spanish across the Caribbean inherited this feature as part of a broader phonological profile shaped by Andalusian input."
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Phonetically, /s/ reduction is often described as a weakening pathway "
        },
        {
          "text": "[s] → [h] → [∅]. ",
          "bold": true
        },
        {
          "text": "That is, a fully articulated sibilant [s] may be realized as such (e.g., [los 'mismos]), an aspirated [h] ([loh 'mihmoh]), and, in some cases, deleted altogether ([lo 'mimo]). In Puerto Rico, /s/ reduction falls within Stage 3 of Lipski's weakening pathway (see below). This system is even more complex, with scholars documenting not only [s], [h], and [∅], but also their voiced counterparts [z] and [ɦ], and a glottal stop [ʔ]  ([loʔ ˈmihmoʔ]). Importantly, the lack of /s/ does not create confusion between words that without /s/ are homophonous (e.g., "
        },
        {
          "text": "mismo",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " and "
        },
        {
          "text": "mimo",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "), as speakers utilize several phonetic strategies to distinguish forms, including vocalic and consonantal lengthening and consonantal strengthening (e.g., "
        },
        {
          "text": "mismo",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " ['mim:o] vs "
        },
        {
          "text": "mimo",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " ['mimo]). "
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The alternation between these forms are not random. Rather, their distribution is conditioned by phonological environment (e.g., whether the /s/ precedes a consonant or a vowel), as well as social and stylistic factors. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
