    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "/s/ in Puerto Rico ",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "textSize": "heading-three",
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "In Puerto Rico, /s/ variation is deeply embedded in social evaluation. Traditionally, full [s] is associated with formality, education, and institutional authority, while aspiration [h] and deletion [∅] are linked to informality and everyday speech. However, these associations are not stable or uniform. Aspirated [h], for example, is often positively evaluated as an authentic marker of Puerto Rican identity, particularly in casual contexts. Deletion [∅], by contrast, is more heavily stigmatized, frequently associated with lack of education or lower socioeconomic status. At the same time, these values are highly context-dependent and mediated by who is perceived to be using the feature."
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "justify",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "url": "https://drive.google.com/file/d/1AzZxTlX98SzLxXRQPwKlhQANKeLMB2hP/view?usp=sharing",
      "caption": "An Indexical Field of /s/ reduction in Puerto Rico",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ],
      "align": "center"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Taken together, /s/ reduction illustrates how a phonological process that originated as a regional feature becomes reinterpreted through social practice. In everyday speech and especially in musical performance, these variants are not simply inherited—they are strategically deployed. This is why /s/ reduction plays such a central role in reggaetón: it has become enregistered as part of the genre’s sonic identity, a stylistic resource that signals Caribbeanness, urbanity, and authenticity, regardless of where the performer is from.\n"
        }
      ],
      "align": "justify"
    },
    {
      "type": "horizontal-separator",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "/s/ in Reggaetón ",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "S-reduction in coda is a very common phonological feature of reggaetón production. In online lyric transcripts, you will find people mark words with etymological /s/ with an ' (e.g., no me mire') to indicate an intentional reduction. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Alveolar Fricatives in Coda Articulation/Orthographic Representation  \nS-Reduction Coda /s/ in Puerto Rico S-Reduction in Reggaetón "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Below are examples that demonstrate claims made in research about the nature of /s/ reduction in reggaetón",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ],
      "align": "center"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "horizontal-separator",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Listen Here ",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The following examples are designed to showcase the findings of research on /s/ reduction in contemporary reggeatón. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "/s/ is seen as a genre-specific index of artistic affiliation. This means that scholars have found  artists reduce /s/ significantly more when performing reggaetón but not other genres. Below are examples of Puerto Rican artists specifically who showcase this pattern. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Ivy Queen "
        }
      ]
    },
